post_text: In honor of Hispanic Heritage Month, we would like to highlight an important event that helped bring the latino civil rights movement to the national level. Please watch and share this video that lead the way for local and national school districts to follow suit in the fight for educational equality.
shared_text:
Neta
November 15, 2018 at 7:37 PM ·

Official trailer 🎬 The Edcouch-Elsa High School Walkout of Nov. 14, 1968, was a defining moment in Rio Grande Valley history and a key component in the Chicano Civil Rights Movement. Fifty years later, we are commemorating the students of 1968 with a short documentary.

Join the documentary premiere --> Historic Edcouch-Elsa 1968 Walkout Documentary Screening

For more info, check out: netargv.com/EE50

As we prepare for the upcoming Sports season we ask that all students in grades 7th, 9th, and 11th and any athlete that may have been injured that required surgery, to please see their physicians for their annual Sports Physical Checkup.

We are anticipating return to play on Sept. 28 for HS Football, Volleyball, and XCountry with modified schedules and taking all the UIL required Protocols and Guidelines to ensure safety of all our student-athletes.

Currently, we are in discussions to ensure safety of all our Jr. High Athletics programs and no decisions have been made as of yet. We will keep you up to date as more information becomes available.

Q&A VIRTUAL LEARNING QUESTIONS
By: Destiny Munoz
Jacket Network

We asked ten students a set of questions dealing with the new look 2020-21 school year and these were their answers:

Question #1: How do you feel about starting the school year 100 percent virtual?
Question #2: What do you miss the most about being in school?
Question #3: What do you hope will happen before the end of the school year?

Jackie Garcia (Senior)
1. Virtual learning is a challenge but after you get used to it it’s pretty easy.
2. What I miss about school is seeing my friends everyday, Friday night lights and pep rally’s.
3. And I hope we can be on campus and make more memories before the end of the school year.

Patriot Day on September 11th honors the memory of the nearly 3,000 innocent victims who lost their lives in the September 11, 2001 terrorist attacks. We dedicate this day to remember those who lost their lives and to the first responders who risked their own lives to save others.

8:46am - American Airlines Flight #11 collides into the World Trade Center

9:03am - United Airlines Flight #175 collides i to the World Trade Center South Tower

9:37am - American Airlines Flight #77 crashes into the Pentagon

10:03am - United Airlines Flight #93 crashes in Skanksville, PA

We stand united. We remember the fallen. We will never forget.

Eehs Cheer is with Aalyah Balderas and 5 others.
September 9 at 10:12 AM ·

On September 9th, National Teddy Bear Day 🧸 honors the history of one of childhood’s favorite toys.

In 1902, American President Theodore Roosevelt refused to shoot a bear cub while hunting in Mississippi. The incident made national news. Clifford Berryman published a cartoon of the event in the Washington Post on November 16th, 1902, and the caricature became an instant classic.

The Berryman cartoon of Teddy Roosevelt and the cub inspired New York store owner Morris Michtom to create a new toy. Mitchtom wrote to ask President Roosevelt to ask permission to name the new toy a “Teddy Bear.” 🧸

We have all had a special cuddly Teddy as a child. No matter what kind of Teddy Bear 🧸 you had, the day is a perfect time to celebrate your childhood stuffed toy!

Lots of learning going on for everyone at LBJ! Students, teachers, paraprofessionals, office staff, administrators and parents have had to learn how to navigate Canvas, Zoom, Seesaw, IXL, Waterford, iReady....not to mention logging on to chromebooks!
But you know what?! That’s what makes us LBJ! We are a learning community that supports each other and will go over and beyond to serve our students and parents. We are so proud of our teachers, students & parents for successfully logging on every day, for not giving up and just pushing forward!
WE ARE LBJ!!! Together we can get through this! Together we are STRONGER!
Have a great weekend, we’ll be back at it on Monday!

August 28 at 9:58 AM ·

Returning to school after a long summer break, is what most students look forward to. This year, we begin school in a way that we have never done so. This video was created to bring awareness to steps that we can take to hopefully return to school. It's a mystery just how long COVID-19 will keep us at a distance. Everything will be back to normal, as we now it, someday, when we aren't six feet apart. Performed by the EEHS Cheer Group and covered by Matthew Rodriguez, EEHS Teacher and lead singer of Southern Ashes. We would like to thank Ms. Telisa Munoz and Mr. Rodriguez for all their hard work in putting together this video project, as well as Mr. Joe Vallejo and Mr. John Cannon for the production of the video.

post_text:
ESTUDIANTES Y PADRES EN EEISD

Debido al aumento de los casos de Corona Virus COVID19 en el valle, y para
garantizar la seguridad de los estudiantes de EEISD y la comunidad, se
canceló la Graduación de Clase Senior programada para el viernes 26 de
junio. En cambio, se producirá un programa virtual de graduación el 26 de Junio 7pm. Nos
disculpamos por no poder tener una graduación tradicional para la Clase
Senior de 2020. Le deseamos a nuestra sobresaliente clase Senior mucho
éxito y lo mejor en sus años futuros.

post_text:
Attention: EEISD Students and Parents.
Due to the increase of Corona Virus
COVID19 cases in the valley, and to ensure the safety of EEISD students and the community, the Senior Class Graduation scheduled Friday, June 26 has been cancelled. Instead a virtual graduation program will be produced, and aired on our district youtube channel on Friday, June 26 at 7 pm. We apologize for not being able to have a traditional graduation for the Senior Class of 2020. We wish our outstanding Senior Class much success and the very best throughout their future years.

Jorge R Gutierrez Early Childhood School
May 29 at 9:43 AM ·

JRG Early Childhood celebrated the End of School Year 2020 with a cheerful parade full of color and joy. It was amazing to see all of our students’ bright smiles, happy to see their teachers one last time before the school year was over. A huge thank you to the City of Edcouch Police Department for keeping us safe throughout our parade route. Thank you also to the EEISD Transportation Department for allowing us to use their school bus. We are very grateful for all the parent and community support throughout the year.

post_text:
We care about the cities of Edcouch and Elsa! And everyday we meet others who care about our community as much as we do. They often ask, "What can I do to make a difference?" This year, the answer is easy. You can make a difference by participating in the 2020 Census. That's because the Census determines how many billions of dollars are allocated every year to health clinics, schools, affordable housing, and hundreds of other critical services and programs that make a difference in our lives every day. It only takes a few minutes, but the impact will be felt for years. When you receive the invitation from the U.S. Census Bureau, complete the simple questionnaire online, by phone, or by mail. And the Census only occurs once every ten years, so don't miss out on your chance to make a difference! Shape your future. START HERE.

Visit 2020census.gov

#everyonecounts

#todos contamos

#2020census

The Edcouch-Elsa Band Experience
Calling all 5th-grade parents and teachers! Next year at David Ybarra Fine Arts Academy students have the chance to join our award-winning band program. Students who join band have the opportunity to learn leadership skills, team building, and have fun in the process. Also, band kids statistically score higher on college entrance exams. Come be part of the biggest family within the Edcouch-Elsa Independent School district spanning over 7-grade levels and 3 campuses. We can't wait to meet you!

Good News Edcouch-Elsa ISD Family AR Testing is now available.
This morning we have worked diligently with Renaissance staff and as of now, our students can quiz on AR from home. We also have MackinVIA where students can log in to read books and then test on AR.

MackinVIA link is found on our website's homepage under "M".
The following are the passwords for each campus that our students need to use to login.

CAMPUS USERNAME PASSWORD

HIGH SCHOOL eehigh eehigh

TRUAN JR HIGH truan truan

JFK jfkee jfkee

LBJ lbjee lbjee

RCR rcree rcree

SGE sgeee sgeee

https://global-zone51.renaissance-go.com/welcomeportal/238728

https://www.mackinvia.com/

Let me know if you have any questions. Have a great day. Stay safe.

Marta Rivera, MLS
Head Librarian
RGV Reads
Edcouch-Elsa ISD

Edcouch-Elsa HS Spring Break Message
According to statistics, car crashes are the leading cause of death for people 15-20 years old The purpose of Shatters Dreams is to bring awareness to the student body of the dangers associated with drinking and/or texting while behind the wheel. This needless suffering is preventable if we stop and make the right choices before getting behind the wheel.

shared_text:
Edcouch-Elsa ISD added 24 new photos — at Edcouch-Elsa High School.
March 12 at 3:17 PM · Elsa, TX ·

"Shattered Dreams" is an educational experience that shows the dangers associated with drinking and driving. It reminds us that too many young lives have already been lost and countless others severely impaired because of the tragic consequences of underage drinking combined with driving. It's about living and dying.

The "Shattered Dreams" program involves the dramatization of an alcohol-related crash on or near a high school campus, complete with fire, police and EMS response, emergency room treatment, funeral hearse, family notifications, and the arrest and booking of the driver.
The crash scene drama is played out before the student body. To give students a better understanding of the number of DWI-related deaths, an individual dressed as the "Grim Reaper" appears periodically as victims start to die. The judge pronounces the deceased.

*Vihuela - 2nd chair Miguel Garza

Victor Cardenas is attending 22nd Annual YellowJacket Relays with Arturo Mata and 28 others at Benny Layton, S.R. Memorial Stadium.
February 15 at 8:52 PM · Elsa, TX ·

Meet was a Huge Sucess. Eventful Day! Two New inductees into the Edcouch-Elsa Track & Field Hall of Fame. Coach Jaime Ochoa has dedicated 37years to Polevaulting and 40years to Edcouch-Elsa Isd. Celinda Caceres was a Powerhouse during her days and still holds records in the Long Jump and 200m Dash.

We also witnessed two of our very own, the Dynamic Duo of Albino Rodriguez and Dominic Medrano sign their letters of intent to continue their acadmic and athletic careers at UTRGV.

Like I said, Eventful day, and none of this would have been possible without the Support of our AD, Admin. Staff, and of course our coaching staff for going above and beyond the call of duty to make this day possible.

Proud to be EDCOUCH-ELSA!

Dear Parents,

Safety is one of our district's top priorities, that's why we're continuing to use SafeSchools Alert, a tip reporting system that allows students, staff, and parents to submit safety concerns to our administration five different ways:

1. App: Search for “SafeSchools Alert” in the App Store to download for free
2. Phone: 956.255.6672
3. Text: Text your tip to 956.255.6672
4. Email: 1423@alert1.us
5. Web: http://1423.alert1.us

Easily report tips on bullying, harassment, drugs, vandalism or any safety issue you're concerned about. Tips may be submitted anonymously too.

Thanks in advance for helping to make our school community a safer place to work and learn! We appreciate your support.

Superintendent of Schools,

Dr. Richard Rivera

First Grade Teacher, Mrs. Rachel Robles, was selected as one of the Top Educators of America for the 2019-2020 school year by The Top Educators of America, a New York-based publication. Mrs. Robles was nominated by our late school secretary, Mrs. Rosa L. Contreras, in the fall semester of 2019. The Top Educators of America recognizes individuals who demonstrate “success and leadership in their field.” For Mrs. Robles, it was an honor and a privilege to be nominated by Mrs. Rosa L. Contreras. At Ruben C. Rodriguez Elementary, we are extremely proud to have Mrs. Rachel Robles as part of our faculty!

February 5 at 11:45 AM ·

For the first semester of the school year, RCR Elementary swept away as one of the highest elementary campuses for student attendance. RCR was recognized by district administrators and board members at the “Night of Champions” for receiving such honor for the 1st and 2nd Six Weeks. January marks another milestone for the campus for receiving such distinction again for the 3rd Six Weeks. This honor would not have been possible without the support of our parents, Mrs. Melissa Mata, and Ms. Sandra Uribe. Thank-you!

ITS TIME ELSA!
On January 25th the Mayor signed a pledge to engage in a healthier life style and to motivate others to do the same. On February 29th the City of Elsa along with Crossfit 107, will be hosting a free 5K walk run event to bring the community together. Everyone is encouraged to attend, make it a family event. You can register online for $2 or in person at Elsa City Hall from 8:30-5:30 or at the Crosfit Box from 5:30-7:30 for free. This is all part of IT'S TIME TEXAS COMMUNITY CHALLENGE!. So we challenge you to come out and participate in our free 5K run walk, and sign a pledge to become healthier.
https://runners956.redpodium.com/1st-annual-caboose-family-fun-run-walk

post_text:
RCR Elementary: Team Quest Competition @ Region One ESC
A group of Edcouch-Elsa's 5th Grade G/T students attended the Region One ESC Team Quest Competition. Out of 24 participating teams from different school districts, RCR students, Janelle Hernandez, Joshua Lopez, Carlos Nino, and Kimberly Rodriguez, placed 3rd overall. Students not only had a blast in the competition, but also learned about challenges, trials, and the importance of archaeology through 5 hands-on challenges in the core areas of science, engineering, technology, math, art, and creativity! Congrats to these students for a job well done!

For more pictures, please visit and like our Facebook page: https://www.facebook.com/RUBENRODRIGUEZELEMENTARY

post_text:
EEHS: Financial Aid Night A Huge Success
Thank you for making Financial Aid Night a HUGE success! It was held on Monday, January 14th. The event addressed and served a need that the parents and students had; how to finance postsecondary education. For the most part, our students will be receiving the entire Pell Grant allotment.

We want to take the time to thank everyone who put this event together EEHS College and Career Readiness, Mrs. Lizette Gonzalez, District Migrant Director Mrs. Vela and our migrant dept. for making personal contact with every migrant senior and inviting the students to Financial Aid Night.

In celebration of School Board Recognition Month, we want to recognize all of our school board members for everything they do for our district. At Carlos F. Truan STEAM Academy we had the honor to host Mr. Robert Peacock. He enjoyed Mariachi music and lunch with our principal, NJHS students and teachers. Mr. Peacock highlighted the unique role school board members play in advocating for quality education for all of our students.

We want to thank you Mr. Robert Peacock for your time and expertise in making important decisions for the education of all our students!

JRG Early Childhood
LAUNCHING THE NEXT GENERATION
In honor of Mr. Chris Morales, teachers and staff at Jorge R. Gutierrez Early Childhood School enjoyed an out of this world Blast Off Breakfast. Mr. Morales was greeted with a cup of fuel and an astronomical pre-flight breakfast before he took off on his mission. Mr. Morales gives countless hours to make decisions for our boys and girls, and for this we are thankful. Mr. Morales is out of this world and one of the best in the universe. A big THANK YOU to Mr. Morales and all board members for their time and commitment, and dedication to the Edcouch-Elsa community.
